Summarizing what we talked about and trying things on my end, comparing with `eth-sig-util` tests, this should include the following logic in one way or another:

```py
    if is_array_type(type_):
        ...
    elif type_ == "bool":
        ...
    elif type_.startswith("bytes") and not is_array_type(type_):
        if not isinstance(value, bytes):
            value = (
                to_bytes(hexstr=value)
                if is_0x_prefixed_hexstr(value)
                else to_bytes(text=value)
                if isinstance(value, str)
                else to_bytes(value)
            )

        return (
            # keccak hash if dynamic `bytes` type
            ("bytes32", keccak(value))
            if type_ == "bytes"
            # if fixed bytesXX type, do not hash
            else ("bytes32", value)
        )
```

Where the helper method `is_0x_prefixed_hexstr()` checks for the `0x` at the beginning. Otherwise, strings are counted as a hexstring if they pass the regex [here](https://github.com/ethereum/eth-utils/blob/e1a395207f26962e49147fc80ccff23f150b2d62/eth_utils/hexadecimal.py#L11-L11), which doesn't require the `0x`. This means a string that is meant to be a string representation of the number "10" is treated as a hex string instead. "0x10" is very different from "10", which is why those tests were failing.

On my end, I included the `is_0x_prefixed_hexstr()` method in your `encode_typed_data/helpers.py` file and it just looks like this:

```py
def is_0x_prefixed_hexstr(value: Any):
    return is_hexstr(value) and value.startswith("0x")
```

